							<h4>Booting Up</h4>
							<p><strong>Booting up</strong>  most simply means to start up your computer. To the computer <strong> user,</strong>  (a user is any person using a computer for work, study, fun or any reason) <strong>booting up</strong> is a pretty simple task; to your computer, however, it is a much more complex task. There is actually a start up program that guides the computer each time it is powered on and makes sure that a list of programs are loaded and the computer is made ready for use until it is powered down or turned off. You will learn a more complete definition of <strong>booting up</strong> in the section about <strong>Computer Memory.</strong> </p>
							<hr>
                            <h4>User Interface</h4>
                            <p>The program that you encounter after the computer boots up is called the <strong>user interface</strong>. It provides a set of commands or menus through which you can interact with the computer to accomplish a task. Historically, computer users have typed commands or made selections from menus with a keyboard and/or a mouse. However, because touch screens are becoming more popular as a way to operate handheld and mobile devices, computers are providing touch screens as well. The user interface must be programmed to accept input from a touch screen.</p>
                            <p>Microsoft Windows is an example of a user interface, and there have been many different versions of Microsoft Windows created over the years. You will learn about the different versions in the section, <strong>Version of Windows and Microsoft Office</strong>.  In most versions of Windows, the first screen you see after the computer boots up is a desktop. You will learn more about the parts of the desktop in the section, <strong>Windows on Your Desktop</strong>. However, it is important to understand the controversy with Windows 8, which introduced major changes to the traditional computer user interface to look more like the user interface experienced by handheld devices such as tablet computers and smart phones.</p>
                            <p>On most handheld devices, the touch screen is utilized. Also, online stores are available on those devices for downloading and purchasing new software or apps (short for applications). Many online services are provided as well. These online services allow the user to sync (synchronize or coordinate) settings, dynamically (automatically) update apps, and share or store information, especially to the cloud or SkyDrive. You will learn more about the cloud and SkyDrives in the section on <strong>Data Storage on the Computer</strong>.</p>
                            <p>So Windows 8 replaced the familiar desktop as the first screen and provided a tiled screen, called the Metro view to compete with user interfaces on touch-friendly, handheld devices. This caused major problems for the user who operated a standard, non-touchscreen computer with a mouse. The familiar Start Button through which all programs were found in previous versions of Windows was replaced by an App list and “Charms” that appear and disappear on the right hand side of the screen. </p>
                            <p>In Windows 8 with a touch screen, you could swipe or scroll the screen up, down, right, or left just like you could on a smart phone or tablet computer. In other words, you interacted with the computer just like you interacted with your smart phone. Although you could still use a mouse with Windows 8, it worked better with a touch screen. Even though you could get back to the familiar desktop by selecting the desktop tile, users were still extremely dissatisfied with the changes in Windows 8. So Microsoft quickly released Windows 8.1 which restored a revised Start Button. However, it did not provide what the traditional Start Button provided. Because Windows 8 versions were not received well, Microsoft plans to go back to the desktop and Start Button for traditional computer users in successive versions.</p>
                            <p>Both the traditional desktop and the Metro view define how the user interfaces or works with the computer. Below is the traditional desktop in Windows.</p>
