mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">or, in some cases, on the side or top, </span>you will see a strip called the <strong>taskbar.</strong> In many versions of Windows, you can right click on the desktop, select <strong>Personalize</strong>, and then <strong>Taskbar and Navigation</strong> to determine the position of the taskbar. For the sake of simplicity in this curriculum, we will assume the taskbar is located at the bottom of the screen. </p>
                            <p>The taskbar has three sections:</p>
							<ol>
								<li>In the far left bottom corner is the  <strong>Start Button.</strong> This is the section where, in many versions of Windows, you can find all of the programs on your computer;</li>
								<li>In the middle of the taskbar you will see the windows or tasks you have open on your computer;</li>
								<li>In the far right bottom section is the <strong>notification section</strong> which usually shows a clock, the volume, date, and other icons that give you information about the programs running on your computer.</li>
