							<h4>Mouse Buttons</h4>
							<br />
							<br />
							<img class="center" src="images/computerbasics/mouse.png" alt="">
							<br />
							<p>Most computer mice have two buttons. The <strong>main or primary button is on the left</strong>  and a <strong> secondary button is on the right.</strong>  These two buttons have different functions. When you are told to <strong>click,</strong>  it means you press and release the primary (left) button only.</p>
							<p>To <strong> right click,</strong>  you press only right button on the mouse.</p>
							<p>Advanced mice may have more buttons with other functions such as a <strong>scroll wheel</strong>  between the buttons which helps you to <strong> scroll or browse</strong>  forward or backward quickly through information in an open window. Roll the wheel toward you to advance forward and away from you to go backwards.</p>
							<p>Sometimes you will click once with the left button and sometimes you need to <strong> double click.</strong>  Double clicking means you click twice on the left button of the mouse quickly. This takes practice. If single clicking does not get you the intended results, try double clicking.</p>
							<p><strong>Click and drag</strong>  means to left click and while holding down the button, drag the mouse.</p>
							<p>To <strong>hover</strong> with your mouse means to hold your mouse pointer over an item on the screen. Sometimes when you hover over an item or icon, a description or explanation of it will pop-up to tell you what that item or icon means.</p>
